# Pokemon Champions — Competitive Doubles Format

Pokemon Champions (Switch, April 2026) is the official VGC platform for the 2026 Pokemon World Championships. It is NOT a mainline game — it has distinct mechanics.

## Game Format: Regulation M-A Doubles

- **Bring 6, pick 4** — each player builds a team of 6 but selects 4 for each battle during a 90-second team preview
- **Double battle** — 2 Pokemon active per side at all times (until one side has fewer remaining)
- **Level 50** — all Pokemon are normalized to level 50 for battle
- **Species clause** — no duplicate species on a team
- **Item clause** — no duplicate held items on a team
- **Limited dex** — ~195 fully-evolved Pokemon from all generations, no unevolved forms. Paldea Origin Mark required.
- **Time limits** — 10 min per player, 90 sec team preview, 60 sec per turn

## Stat System (Different from Mainline Games)

Pokemon Champions replaces the traditional EV/IV system:

- **IVs do not exist** — all Pokemon have an implicit 31 IV in every stat
- **Stat Points replace EVs** — 66 total points, max 32 per stat (vs 510 EVs / 252 per stat in mainline)
- **Stat formula at level 50:**
  `floor((floor((2 * Base + 31 + StatPoints) * 50 / 100) + 5) * Nature)`
  HP uses a different formula (add Level + 10 instead of + 5, no nature multiplier)
- **Natures (Stat Alignment)** — still +10% / -10% to two non-HP stats, freely selectable
- **Key difference from EVs**: 66 stat points gives 1 more point of budget than the classic EV equivalent of 65 (510 EVs / 8 = 63.75, rounded = 63, plus the first 4 of each stat = ~65). This matters for specific calcs.

## Battle Gimmick: Mega Evolution via Omni Ring

- **Mega Evolution** — available for 59 species. Requires Mega Stone held item. Once per battle; if your Mega faints, you cannot Mega another.
- Terastallization, Z-Moves, and Dynamax are NOT currently available in Regulation M-A.

## Key Competitive Mechanics (Doubles-Specific)

- **Protect** — blocks all damage for one turn; fails more often if used consecutively. Central to doubles strategy.
- **Speed control** — Tailwind (x2 speed, 4 turns), Trick Room (slow moves first, 5 turns), Icy Wind / Electroweb (lower opponent speed). Speed recalculates after each action within a turn.
- **Weather** — Rain, Sun, Sand, Snow. Set by abilities (Drizzle, Drought, etc.) or moves. Lasts 5 turns (8 with held item). Affects damage, speed (via Swift Swim, etc.), and enables/disables certain moves.
- **Field conditions are turn-counted** — planning around their expiry is a core skill the agent must learn.
- **Intimidate** — lowers opposing Attack on switch-in. Extremely common in doubles; affects team preview decisions.
- **Fake Out** — priority move that flinches, only works on first turn after switch-in. Defines many opening sequences.
- **Redirecting** — moves like Follow Me / Rage Powder force opponents to target the redirector. Key doubles mechanic.

